		</table><h2>Research Interests</h2>		<h2>Numerical analysis, the design and evaluation of computational methods</h2>
		<div class="research_interest">
			<p>Specific interests: stochastic computation with applications in computational biology and mathematical finnace.</p>
<p>For much more detail please go to my <a href="/d.j.higham">Personal Home Page</a>.</p>
		</div>		<h2>Recent Publications</h2>
			<dl class="publications">		<dt>Googling the Brain: Discovering hierarchical and asymmetric network structures, with applications in neuroscience</dt>
		<dd>Crofts JJ and Higham DJ<br /><span class="journaltitle">University of Strathclyde Mathematics and Statistics Research Report</span>, <span class="pubyear">2010</span>, <span class="pubvolno">#35</span>, 20  </dd>		<dt>Communicability across evolving networks</dt>
		<dd>Grindrod P, Higham DJ, Parsons MC and Estrada E<br /><span class="journaltitle">University of Strathclyde Mathematics and Statistics Research Report</span>, <span class="pubyear">2010</span>, <span class="pubvolno">#32</span>, 20  </dd>		<dt>Mathematics faces up to facebook</dt>
		<dd>Higham DJ, Grinrod P and Estrada E<br /><span class="journaltitle">University of Strathclyde Mathematics and Statistics Research Report</span>, <span class="pubyear">2010</span>, <span class="pubvolno">#19</span>, 17  </dd>		<dt>Random graph models and their application to protein-protein interaction networks</dt>
		<dd>Higham DJ and Natasa Przulj<br /><span class="journaltitle">University of Strathclyde Mathematics and Statistics Research Report</span>, <span class="pubyear">2010</span>, <span class="pubvolno">#18</span>, 35  </dd>		<dt>Stochastic ordinary differential equations in applied and computational mathematics</dt>
		<dd>Higham DJ<br /><span class="journaltitle">University of Strathclyde Mathematics and Statistics Research Report</span>, <span class="pubyear">2010</span>, <span class="pubvolno">#7</span>, 1-32  </dd></dl><p style="margin-top: 1em;">View all of <a href="/people/academic/des_higham/publications">Des Higham's Publications</a>.</p><h3>Complex Networks in Biology</h3>		<div class="vacancy">
			<p class="refNo"><strong>Reference No.</strong>: DJH1</p>
			<p><strong>Supervisor</strong>: <a href="/people/academic/des_higham">Professor Des Higham</a></p>
			
			<p><strong>Date Advertised:</strong> 6th February 2007</p>
			<p>Please contact <a href="/people/academic/des_higham">Professor Des Higham</a> for further information.</p>
			<p>
  Several areas of experimental cell biology have produced networks. In mathematical terms these are graphs: eg the nodes may be proteins and a pair of proteins may be linked by an edge if they take part in a common function.
</p>
<p>
  A current research activity involves modelling these networks (eg what underlying mechanisms are producing the connectivity patterns?) and searching for patterns (eg can we indentify proteins that have similar biological roles?).
</p>
<p>
  PhD work in this area would involve a mix of computation (with matrices), discrete mathematics and possibly statistics.
</p>
<p>
  There is also a possibility to engage with biological colleagues at the University of Glasgow and/or the Beatson Cancer Research Institute in Bearsden.
</p>
		</div><h3>Stochastic Computation for Cell Biology</h3>		<div class="vacancy">
			<p class="refNo"><strong>Reference No.</strong>: DJH2</p>
			<p><strong>Supervisor</strong>: <a href="/people/academic/des_higham">Professor Des Higham</a></p>
			
			<p><strong>Date Advertised:</strong> 20th November 2007</p>
			<p>Please contact <a href="/people/academic/des_higham">Professor Des Higham</a> for further information.</p>
			<p>
  DNA, mRNA and proteins are the fundamental building blocks that govern what happens inside our cells.
</p>
<p>
  Some simple mathematical models have recently been developed and studied with the aim of understanding the control processes taking place.
</p>
<p>
  Mathematical models and computational algorithms must take account of both the inherent noise in the system and the vast range of scales (fast/slow reactions many/few molecules of a species).
</p>
<p>
  This project would analyse some recent models and develop efficient simulation tools. 
</p>
<p>
  This work would involve a mixture of analysis (differential equations), stochastics, and computation and there is potential for collaboration with life scientists.
</p>
		</div>
			</div>			
